2021.ai project deployer

¶

Increase recognizeability and readability for data science projects.

Easy to deploy

pip install cookiecutter
cookiecutter git@gitlab.com:2021AI/cookiecutter.git

Will ask you a series of questions that are fomatted directly into your README.md

{
    "project_name": "Project name",
    "description": "A short description of the project.",
    "data_scientist": "Data scientist running the project",
    "owner_mail": "your @2021.ai email",

    "repo_name": "{{ cookiecutter.project_name.lower().replace(' ', '_') }}",
    "repo_link": "Link to Gitlab repo",
    "drive_link": "Link to Google Drive folder",
    "hubspot_link": "Link to Hubspot",
    "forecast_link": "Link to ForecastIT",

    "business_contact": "Business contact information to customer partner",
    "tech_contact": "Technical Contact information to customer",
    "support_contact": "Support and Service desk contact information to customer",

    "business_owner": "2021 business owner",
    "tech_owner": "2021 technical owner"

}

Deploys a standard project structure (increases readability and recognizability)

├── data
│   ├── external
│   ├── interim
│   ├── processed
│   └── raw
├── docs
├── LICENSE
├── Makefile
├── models
├── notebooks
├── README.md
├── references
├── reports
│   └── figures
├── requirements.txt
├── src
│   ├── __init__.py
│   ├── data
│   ├── models
│   ├── preprocessing
│   ├── production
│   └── visualization
└── tox.ini
  • Make documentation with one line 
    make doc
  • Run multi-syntax lint with one line 
    make clean
  • Run parts of the pipeline with 
    make preprocessing optimise train predict

2021.ai pipelines

¶

Data ingestion, visualisation, preprocessing and model building.

  • data wrangling & preprocessing
  • model building

data wrangling & preprocessing¶

  • Data ingest should have some standards (e.g. textfiles, .db, HDFS).
  • Output standard report with figures and printed information about the raw & preprocessed data.
  • Standard preprocessing with easy-to-call label/one-hit encoding, standardsation, etc.

model building¶

  • Inherently data & problem dependent (e.g. clustering, regression, nlp, etc.)
  • Build to "solve 80% of the problem in 20% of the time"

2021.ai production pod

¶

A standard environment to support the process of putting machine learning models in production.

  1. Loading raw data to appropriate storage which is kept in a data volume.
  2. When data is detected, run the ML pipeline.
  3. Return the preprocesed data and model output to storage. Save the model in a volume.
  4. Given the model, deploy the appropriate app (e.g. classification or text-search).

2021.data science workflow

¶

A flexible styleguide & a set of not-so-flexible rules for how to develop software in the 2021.ai data science team.

styleguide

¶

Don't Repeat Yourself (DRY)

Don't reinvent something that you (or someone else) already done.
Use Auto-ML, SKLearn, etc. and try to plan out if your code actually adds something useful.

Principle of least astonishment

If a necessary feature has a high astonishment factor, it may be necessary to redesign the feature.
When your colleages get that confused sad look on their faces when they see the code you've written, you probably need to rewrite some things.

You Ain't Gonna Need It (YAGNI)

Write code that does one thing well.
Dont overengineer code unless its deeply nessesary.

rules

¶

Minimum requirements

All commits (even the initial) to master must come with full documentation (README.md, docstrings, etc.) including a step-by-step guide on how to run the project, all unit tests included and a complete source library with the code required. All of this must be completely dockerized, unless there is a really good reason not to. Until this is done, keep development in the development branch and keep the master clean.

All parts of any project (e.g. preprocessing, training, etc.) must be documented in Gitlab using the Kanban issue tracker. There are already [several examples](https://gitlab.com/2021ds-development/nlp_pipeline/boards) on how this is done on our Gitlab. When a piece of code is written, refer to the issue it solves in the commit message. E.g. 

git add preprocessing.py
git commit -m "label encoding #6"
git push -u origin development

Customer project requirements

All customer projects must fulfill the minimum requirements. Further, all customer projects must be deployed with the cookiecutter and the mandatory questions must be answered. Do not commit a project to master without this information.

Internal development requirements

All internal development projects must fulfill the minimum requirements. Further, every internal development project must be aimed at either 1) developing a fully fledged pip-installable package 2) contributing to an existing package. Further, the documentation should cover a few examples that import the code and demonstrate use in a well-explained notebook.

Don't develop in notebooks

Feel free to play around in notebooks, explore data, design functions etc. in a development branch, but please document your logic in the notebook and git issues. Also, notebooks do not count as source code. These must be independent .py files that live in their respective folders - or in other words, live up to the minimum requirements.
